Our PIRE project was "Collaborative Research and Training in Social Context, Population Processes, and Environmental Change." Environmental changes are often produced by social and economic processes that operate across international borders. In fact, changes in distant countries can have important environmental consequences in the United States. To help equip the next generation of American scientists with the tools needed to work in successful collaboration with scientists in other countries we specifically designed our project to put American trainees into multinational collaborative teams. Because scientific advance in this area also requires multiple types of expertise &ndash; spanning both the ecological and social sciences &ndash; these teams were also explicitly multidisciplinary. Our construction of these teams put each junior scientist into direct collaboration with multiple scientists from other fields of study and other countries, giving American undergraduates, graduate students, post-doctoral trainees, and junior faculty opportunities to build skills in a career of advancing the global science of studying environmental change.

Our research focused on change over time in human-environment interactions in the two most populous regions of the world: South Asia and China. Building on long-term studies of communities, families, land cover, and endangered species in Chitwan, Nepal and Wolong, China, our teams took a new multidisciplinary systems science approach to the integration of population change, social organization, land cover and habitat. Growing populations, rapidly changing economies, unique biodiversity and complex institutional structures combined to make these two sites ideal for advancing and testing theoretical and statistical models of how social and environmental phenomena change over time. Our research used an innovative combination of methods from several different areas of science, including community-level surveys, the analysis of satellite imagery, computational analysis of geographic data, sophisticated statistical models, and computer simulation models.. These tools gave us the means to link change over time in the social organization of communities to change over time in family and population events, to change over time in land use and land cover, to change over time in habitats. Each of these dimensions of change is itself complex and the relations among them are more complex because change in each has the possibility of creating change in any other.

By advancing this area of science we were able to produce:

Crucial improvements in the case-specific understanding of human processes affecting local vegetation and habitats for three important endangered species (pandas, rhinos, and tigers); 
Equally important advances in understanding the ways through which changes in land cover and species diversity affect the nearby human population;
A new set of tools for comprehensively comparing how these dynamic processes occur within different countries; 
Both the models and methods needed to launch a new field of science investigating the human-environment relationships across long distances, spanning international borders.


The project produced both: 1) A new cohort of young scientists able to work in international, cross-disciplinary collaborations to advance this science and teach it to others, and; 2) A new theoretical and methodological framework for conducting multi-site global research on human-environment interactions. Through the project our team was also able to make substantial advances in institutionalized connections between U.S. universities (Arizona State University, the University of Michigan, Michigan State University, the University of North Carolina &ndash; Chapel Hill, and San Diego State University) and collaborative partner institutions in Nepal and China. The broader impacts of these advances include a more internationally engaged scientific and educational climate at key U.S....
